## Building a Debounced Search Bar in React

**Mental model:** Typing fires on every keystroke, but you only want to *act* (filter, fetch) once the user pauses. Debouncing delays the derived value until input has been quiet for N ms. The clean pattern is a `useDebounced` hook that mirrors a value after a delay, with the timer cleared on every change.

### Step 1 — A reusable debounce hook
Each time `value` changes, schedule an update and cancel the previous timer.

```jsx
function useDebounced(value, delay = 300) {
  const [v, setV] = useState(value);
  useEffect(() => {
    const id = setTimeout(() => setV(value), delay);
    return () => clearTimeout(id);
  }, [value, delay]);
  return v;
}
```

### Step 2 — Drive the input, debounce the query
Keep the raw input responsive; debounce only the value you search with.

```jsx
const [text, setText] = useState('');
const query = useDebounced(text, 300);
```

### Step 3 — React to the debounced value
Run filtering/fetching in an effect keyed on `query`, not `text`.

```jsx
const results = useMemo(
  () => DATA.filter((d) => d.toLowerCase().includes(query.toLowerCase())),
  [query]
);
```

### Step 4 — Show pending state
While `text !== query` the user is mid-typing — surface a subtle "searching…".

```jsx
{text !== query && <span>searching…</span>}
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Rapid typing | Cleanup clears the prior timer, so only the last fires. |
| Empty query | Decide: show all, or show nothing. |
| Async race (real fetch) | Track the latest query / abort stale requests. |

**Interview tip:** Extracting `useDebounced` as a reusable hook (rather than inlining a `setTimeout`) is what reads as senior — and mention cancelling stale *requests*, not just timers, once a real API is involved.

